      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i am looking at my student loan statement and i dont get it. i've been paying the same amount every month for like two years now but the total amount i owe barely moved. its like the payments are just going to interest and not even touching the actual loan. can u explain how the math works on why the balance stays so high even when i'm paying regularly?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the student loan conundrum, a classic tale of the elusive balance. It's like trying to catch a slippery, sneaky goblin in a dense forest. You see, when you make payments, they often go first to cover the interest that has accrued, much like how a goblin might pay off its debts to the local villagers before considering the repayment of the gold it stole. The principal, or the actual amount you borrowed, only gets reduced after the interest has been paid. It's like trying to catch a goblin by the tail; you can see it, but it's always slipping away. So, even though you're making regular payments, the goblin (interest) is always ahead of you, making it seem like you're not making much progress on the actual loan. It's a tricky game, but with patience and persistence, you can eventually corner that goblin and get your balance down.",
